I got the Rose Oolong Peach Cake + Honeycomb Dalgona Latte and my friend got the Vanilla Strawberry Shortcake + Iced Shaken Lychee Black Tea.

I would highly recommend the rose peach cake as it's something I haven't been able to get anywhere else and it tasted divine! The rest was sweet and tasted exactly as expected, especially the strawberry cake and the lychee black tea. Not to make that sound bad, they're staples in every store for a reason (they never miss)!! Though, not going to lie, wasn't a huge fan of the honeycomb in my dalgona latte as it was too sweet and it was slightly unnerving every time I'd encounter its crunchy texture. Still drank it all, but probably wouldn't get it again...

Other than that, the decor was nice and clean and the atmosphere was quiet and serene. Also, it's a little on the expensive side... so definitely more of an experience than a regular hang-out spot. Hope the employees enjoyed the relaxing morning as it seemed like a slow shift (to be fair we went around brunch time on a Tuesday). Tldr, worth it to try the rose oolong peach cake and experience the fun of the stacking cake cups.

featured_reviews.review_id:
We hired pretty in pink management to tend bar at our wedding this past weekend and it was Andrea. We had a terrible experience. I hope no other bride has to deal with this company.

First, she showed up late even though we had discussed her arriving early to set up before the wedding reception. We had a line up of people at the bar with no bartender before she even arrived. She also said she was arriving with a complete bar set up with cups and martini shakers as our signature drink was a martini.
Andrea did not bring nearly enough cups to the event and was telling guests to keep their plastic cups. She was free pouring all the martinis and was not even using all the ingredients that were laid out for her.

The biggest issue we had was we agreed on either a prepaid tip in advance or a tip jar. We decided on a prepaid tip from us so our wedding guests would not have to tip. Andrea asked us how she would approach guests who wanted to tip her anyways. We simply told her to tell guests that the bride and groom were taking care of gratuity. This is not uncommon at all with weddings, and was already agreed upon in an email that we would pay the tip in advance. She then took tips throughout the night and ended up leaving with a large tip jar including multiple bills.. we had a toonie bar. I can't help but assume she took money from our cash made from the bar and helped herself.

I am only writing this review because this was one of the most important days of our lives and we feel so taken advantage of. Such unprofessional and shady service and I hope no other bride has to deal with this company or wage their money on this terrible experience. I asked for my original tip back and was ignored.

I hope other brides read this and DO NOT HIRE this company.

I chose the Forward Care East Clinic for my mother in law as its close to where she lives, the doctor is caring (Dr Jeffrey Lau) and the reception staff is very efficient.

Pre-Covid, when my mother in law had some dizzy episodes on a Saturday, we call the office, they fit her in with another doctor in the office and follow up with a letter to Emergency.

Currently, they do either phone appointments or in office appointments and most times when we are in the phone appointment, if the doctor needs to see what is concerning (a rash, take blood pressure, etc.), they do their best to find time to let you come in, luckily for us it was within the same day.

They referred my mother in law for a geriatrician, and Dr Zhang is also located in the same office. Very efficient in communication and coordination. Before the Geriatrician appointment, the staff called us twice with reminders. I appreciate the calls and reminders.

The online booking is the only negative. We get email notification to book for flu shots, etc but our doctor was not set up, or won't allow on the booking site.  Most times it doesn't work, so best to call the office.

Day 1:
Phone was working fine, including vibration and haptics. I was using the phone up to the last minute to browse the internet a bit while waiting, and the haptics were still working that time. My Pixel 5's battery capacity was low, so I decided to get a battery replacement at the store. I took the phone to the shop on Fraser Street, and was charged $110 and the warranty claims to repair all issues stemming from their repair.

I picked up the phone 5pm same day and I was told leave the screen alone after sealing. Later in the night when I think the screen glue's solid enough, I noticed the phone vibration wasn't working.

Day 2:
10am in the morning: I went back to the shop to fix the vibration because. The male employee who looked at the phone, checked the vibration setting, agreed that it isn't working, and said the phone can be ready for pick up around 5pm.
2pm: I checked with the store to see if the repair's been done. I was told it's in progress.
4pm: I was told was still being fixed, and it'd be fixed before the store closes at 8pm.
730pm: Tried calling them several times between 6pm to 7pm, and I didn't get a phone call back from them, so I went to the store and found it already closed.

Day 3:
There was no communication from them for the whole day despite calling them to ask and getting voice mail. When I went to the store, my phone still had its screen removed. I was also told that the senior technician would come in the morning the next day, that it'll be fixed by 3pm tomorrow.

Day 4:
I went to the store at 3pm. My phone's vibration didn't work when picked up, had the setting looked through by the front desk employee. She confirmed that there's no settings. However, she also refused to accept that the battery replacement caused the vibration issues. As of midnight, the phone still had no vibration.

Day 5:
I went in again, and the same female employee went through the vibration test app and all the settings, and so did the older guy with glasses. However, they were insistent that the battery replacement didn't cause the vibration.

When I asked the lady how are they sure that they didn't cause the damage. She claimed that their technicians "know everything". After a while they had the technician to come and talk to me again. When I asked the technician himself what's the problem with the vibration motor, he said didn't know why and that maybe my phone's been like this before I came to them.

The technician claimed that they do not touch the vibration motor at all so it couldn't have been their fault. He wrote that they can't open the phone again because the screen might break, even though the Gorilla Glass screen can withstand 500C easily. And that they won't cover a screen broken due to their own repairs.

As such, it's best to take the technician's advice to heart and not go to Fix 4 U Cellular and that there are more professional, competent, ethical, and knowledgeable cell phone repair shops elsewhere.

Phone was working fine, including vibration and haptics. I was using the phone up to the last minute to browse the internet a bit while waiting, and the haptics were still working that time. My Pixel 5's battery capacity was low, so I decided to get a battery replacement at the store. I took the phone to the shop on Fraser Street, and was charged $110 and the warranty claims to repair all issues stemming from their repair.

I picked up the phone 5pm same day and I was told leave the screen alone after sealing. Later in the night when I think the screen glue's solid enough, I noticed the phone vibration wasn't working.

Day 2:
10am in the morning: I went back to the shop to fix the vibration because. The male employee who looked at the phone, checked the vibration setting, agreed that it isn't working, and said the phone can be ready for pick up around 5pm.
2pm: I checked with the store to see if the repair's been done. I was told it's in progress.
4pm: I was told was still being fixed, and it'd be fixed before the store closes at 8pm.
730pm: Tried calling them several times between 6pm to 7pm, and I didn't get a phone call back from them, so I went to the store and found it already closed.

Day 3:
There was no communication from them for the whole day despite calling them to ask and getting voice mail. When I went to the store, my phone still had its screen removed. I was also told that the senior technician would come in the morning the next day, that it'll be fixed by 3pm tomorrow.

Day 4:
I went to the store at 3pm. My phone's vibration didn't work when picked up, had the setting looked through by the front desk employee. She confirmed that there's no settings. However, she also refused to accept that the battery replacement caused the vibration issues. As of midnight, the phone still had no vibration.

Day 5:
I went in again, and the same female employee went through the vibration test app and all the settings, and so did the older guy with glasses. However, they were insistent that the battery replacement didn't cause the vibration.

When I asked the lady how are they sure that they didn't cause the damage. She claimed that their technicians "know everything". After a while they had the technician to come and talk to me again. When I asked the technician himself what's the problem with the vibration motor, he said didn't know why and that maybe my phone's been like this before I came to them.

The technician claimed that they do not touch the vibration motor at all so it couldn't have been their fault. He wrote that they can't open the phone again because the screen might break, even though the Gorilla Glass screen can withstand 500C easily. He added that if I take responsibility for the screen they can do it for a "little charge" of $30. And stresses that phone screens are very expensive.

It sounded like an insinuation an accident would happen to my phone if I kept pushing for warranty repair. For him to do his job, he'd have to remove the screen from every phone to do his work. For someone who does his daily work around phones, he lacked confidence in himself, otherwise he wouldn't ask clients responsible for the cost of broken glass screen and charge the more for extra repairs. Therefore, by asking me to take responsibility for the cost of the screen in case he damages it, he's being honest about his lack of ability (or care) to fix my problem. And that they won't cover a screen broken due to their own repairs.

As such, it's best to take the technician's advice to heart and not go to Fix 4 U Cellular and that there are more professional, competent, ethical, and knowledgeable cell phone repair shops elsewhere.

featured_reviews.review_id: We recently moved homes so we had to find a new vet in our area. I saw the reviews for Vancouver East Veterinary Walk-In Clinic so we booked our cat in here. Sadly, this was a huge mistake on our part. We took our cat in for her annual checkup. All of the documents were transferred from our previous vet to this one, so it should have her up to date vaccine information and other health background. Unfortunately, Dr. Shura didn't even pay attention to her vaccination history anyways, and despite our cat having gotten her 3-year vaccines in 2018, he said it was done in 2017 and then vaccinated her anyways. I didn't notice this until I got home and saw my previous invoices from the previous vet that said she last got the vaccination in 2018. A few days after we got home from the vet, my cat's hair started falling out in the area where the vaccination was injected. We tried calling Vancouver East Veterinary Walk-In Clinic on Wednesday at around 10AM and there was no pick-up (they are closed most of the week, open only for limited hours in the afternoon), no voice mail, and no emergency line you can call. We ended up having to drive back to our old vet to get her looked at because that was our only option. I understand that adverse side effect may happen after a vaccination, but I am very disappointed that the vet misread her vaccination history and gave her something she didn't need, and also we weren't able to reach them or an alternate number. When we were getting our cat looked at, Mr. Shura said to us that he doesn't like to overvaccinate animals because he'll get our money through teeth cleanings anyways (he had recommended a teeth cleaning for our cat). I couldn't tell if he was a vet or a used car salesman.
